[normal]disbenefits
[normal] for a particular bid, are they incorporated into the assessment of whether a bid should go ahead? Is it just looking at all the factors in a general sense or is there some kind of ranking process? How is it done?
[normal]Alex Wilson[bold]: There is no magic in this. We essentially add up all the costs—so that is all the public sector costs but it can also be the environmental costs—all the costs of a particular project on one side.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q64 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Would that include things like air quality implications and remediation that would have be dealt with if you had a huge number of, say, transport journeys coming in?
[normal]Alex Wilson[bold]: Let me give you an example. That is probably the easiest way of doing it. The project will deliver £1.9 of quantified benefits for every £1 of public support. That is in terms of what we have appraised. The applicant presents research findings on the potential social and environmental benefits of the project, including estimates using 
[normal]TfL’s
[normal] Pedestrian Environment Review System and 
[normal]DfT’s
[normal] models of carbon reduction, accident reduction and journey times. These benefits approximate to over £20 million over 10 years. The results cannot be verified at this stage but if added to the employment impacts would increase the benefit cost ratio to four.
[normal]That was a project that was supported by Ministers on the basis of this additional information that was provided by the applicant, in terms of social and environmental costs and benefits. In terms of where ministerial decisions come in, they then conditionally allocate funding. 
[normal]Then we go out and essentially check the truthfulness of the bid and the claims around that, and then the decisions are finalised. Those numbers are checked during the due diligence stage. I hope that gives you an example, some sense of how we try and factor those in. We don’t have the expertise to do absolutely everything but we do try and capture as much as we can.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q65 [bold]&#xa0; 
